group after his own brother,
Rigoberto, disappeared

20:27.860 --> 20:31.130 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
trying to enter the U.S. through
here in 2009.

20:31.163 --> 20:36.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
His coyote, or human smuggler,
confessed he'd
abandoned Rigoberto during his
last breaths.

20:36.335 --> 20:40.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELY ORTIZ (through translator):
I would think,
where's my brother?

20:40.739 --> 20:42.575 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What happened to him?

20:42.608 --> 20:44.243 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
How did he die?

20:44.276 --> 20:48.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A thousand thoughts went through
my head.

20:48.314 --> 20:52.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I told myself, I'm not going
to leave
my brother lying out there.

20:52.318 --> 20:56.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Ortiz called the
Mexican consulates,
Border Patrol and other
agencies.

20:56.288 --> 21:00.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ELY ORTIZ (through translator):
I asked everyone
for help, and nobody would help
me.

21:00.392 --> 21:05.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: So he went out on
foot, with
the help of human rights
activist named Rafael

21:05.097 --> 21:06.031 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Hernandez.

21:06.065 --> 21:08.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Together, they found his
brother's body.

21:08.100 --> 21:10.870 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was closure for the Ortiz
family.

21:10.903 --> 21:15.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Inspired, Ortiz launched Aguilas
del Desierto.

21:15.741 --> 21:20.546 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He chose the name Aguilas
because of the eagle's
powerful eyesight and wingspan.

21:20.579 --> 21:22.348 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
His volunteers walk into the
desert.

21:22.381 --> 21:25.217 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Some stay with the cars to
rescue us if necessary.

21:25.251 --> 21:32.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ortiz reminds us not to lose
sight of each
other, for safety.

21:32.558 --> 21:36.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Along the coyote arroyo, the
earth is unusually
fertile for a desert.

21:36.862 --> 21:41.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's one of the most transited
border routes
precisely because there's so
much vegetation

21:41.100 --> 21:42.902 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for cover.

21:42.935 --> 21:48.073 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But that means it's also
impossible to follow
Ortiz's mandate to keep an eye
on each other.

21:48.107 --> 21:54.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's people to my left inside
of the brush
and to my right.

21:54.547 --> 22:00.886 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Signs of migrants are
everywhere, tossed Red
Bulls, backpacks, dolls.

22:00.920 --> 22:02.788 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Here's a toy.

22:02.821 --> 22:06.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And drug mules' shoes with
carpet strips on
the bottom to cover tracks.

22:06.058 --> 22:07.860 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There are all over the place.

22:07.893 --> 22:12.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most prevalent are these black
gallon jugs,
which smugglers sell as a sort
of supernatural,

22:12.965 --> 22:14.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
strength-inducing water.

22:14.500 --> 22:17.069 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm following a volunteer named
Jose Genis.

22:17.102 --> 22:21.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says it's hard to spot bodies
in this area
because of all the foliage.

22:21.707 --> 22:24.810 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Dying migrants often crawl
beneath trees seeking
shade.

22:24.843 --> 22:28.581 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSE GENIS, Volunteer: And it
makes it difficult
for us to find them because they
kind of blend

22:28.614 --> 22:30.316 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in, especially after a body has
been decomposing.

22:30.349 --> 22:33.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Genis is a Navy
veteran and
a licensed EMT.

22:33.619 --> 22:38.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On previous searches, he has
found dehydrated
migrants trying to enter the
U.S. illegally.

22:38.924 --> 22:43.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has helped save their lives,
treating them
until Border Patrol could come
take them to

22:43.729 --> 22:45.464 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the hospital.

22:45.497 --> 22:50.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOSE GENIS: I feel American,
but, at the same
time, I have my roots from
Mexico, so I try

22:50.736 --> 22:52.605 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to help out as much as I can.

22:52.638 --> 22:55.007 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: The heat is
oppressive, even
through the trees.

22:55.040 --> 22:58.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are snakes and scorpions
and cattle
skeletons.

22:58.811 --> 23:00.980 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We keep losing each other.

23:01.013 --> 23:06.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We repeatedly have to stop and
regroup, finding
each other by blowing whistles.

23:06.785 --> 23:11.557 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have to make it out before
sunset, when
smugglers inhabit this terrain.

23:11.590 --> 23:13.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But we're not covering nearly
enough ground.

23:13.259 --> 23:16.128 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOSE GENIS: If anything, we have
one-and-a-quarter
miles.

23:16.161 --> 23:19.298 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: We press on.

23:19.331 --> 23:24.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Genis and I find a Bible
crawling with insects.

23:24.870 --> 23:28.374 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I wonder if the person who
dropped it made
it out of this desert alive.

23:28.407 --> 23:34.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hundreds of people die crossing
the border
each year from things like
dehydration or

23:34.380 --> 23:35.414 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
hypothermia.

23:35.447 --> 23:39.251 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
In Arizona alone, the death
count is astounding.

23:39.285 --> 23:42.588 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Official figures exclude the
countless bodies
that are never found.

23:42.621 --> 23:47.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ev Meade of the Trans Border
Institute says
border deaths since the 1990s
range as high

23:48.027 --> 23:49.495 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as 10,000.

23:49.528 --> 23:52.331 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
EV MEADE, Trans Border
Institute: Yes, this
is a large number of people.

23:52.364 --> 23:55.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this is the kind of number
we talk about
when we talk about an armed
conflict or a

23:55.601 --> 23:57.269 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
war.

23:57.303 --> 24:00.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: He says the
deaths are linked
to U.S. border fence
construction.

24:00.406 --> 24:04.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Border crossing deaths were
almost unheard
of until the U.S. built long
stretches of

24:04.176 --> 24:06.045 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
border fence in the '90s.

24:06.078 --> 24:13.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, about 700 miles of the
2,000-mile border
are fenced, mostly around
cities.

24:13.185 --> 24:18.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This has forced migrants onto
remote, dangerous
routes through the desert, with
its extreme

24:18.123 --> 24:19.858 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
temperatures.

24:19.892 --> 24:23.429 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Donald Trump has
already signed
a directive to start building a
border wall.

24:23.462 --> 24:25.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP, President of the
United States:
We're going to build the wall.

24:25.464 --> 24:29.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Meade says
Trump's wall could
increase migrant deaths by
funneling them

24:29.501 --> 24:31.670 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
onto still more dangerous
crossing routs.

24:31.704 --> 24:33.539 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Some are dying on the way.

24:33.572 --> 24:39.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EV MEADE: We just really haven't
had a serious
policy discussion or a public
discussion about

24:39.078 --> 24:41.980 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the humanitarian consequences of
the building
of the wall.

24:42.014 --> 24:45.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Back in the
desert, we pass
barbed-wire fencing.

24:45.551 --> 24:49.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Could it be the fencing referred
to in the
text message?

24:49.955 --> 24:51.957 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Suddenly, someone finds
something.

24:51.991 --> 24:54.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I scramble up a hill, following
Genis.

24:54.760 --> 24:57.296 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It might be him, but we don't
know.

24:57.329 --> 25:00.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
First, I see the skull.

25:00.999 --> 25:05.270 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A few meters away are the legs,
clothed in
pants.

25:05.304 --> 25:08.907 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The body has been torn apart by
coyotes or
some other animal.

25:08.941 --> 25:12.878 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Genis says the body looks like
it's been decomposing
for about a month.

25:12.911 --> 25:16.014 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Marco Antonio disappeared a
month ago.

25:16.048 --> 25:22.955 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MAXIMO GARCIA, Volunteer
(through translator):
Unfortunately, we just found
remains of a

25:22.988 --> 25:24.056 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
human being.

25:24.089 --> 25:28.260 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're going to investigate to
see if it's
him.

25:28.293 --> 25:35.334 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEAN GUERRERO: Garcia calls his
relatives
to tell them what we have found.

25:35.367 --> 25:38.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The Aguilas get to work.

25:38.437 --> 25:39.805 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They can't touch the body.

25:39.838 --> 25:41.673 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It could be a crime scene.

25:41.707 --> 25:46.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They note the coordinates of the
remains,
which they will share with local
police.

25:46.512 --> 25:51.150 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Officials will pick up the body
and take it
to the medical examiner for DNA
analyses.

25:51.183 --> 25:57.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The men improvise a marker out
of a balloon
they find to help officials spot
the body.

25:57.089 --> 26:01.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Back at the vehicles, Garcia
thanks the Aguilas
for the search.

26:01.460 --> 26:04.196 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says they were the only
people willing
to help him.

26:04.229 --> 26:12.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Jean
Guerrero
along the U.S.-Mexican border.

26:12.337 --> 26:21.180 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

26:21.213 --> 26:26.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
fighting disease
in the most polluted city on
Earth; and why

26:26.819 --> 26:33.258 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are presidential sculptures
sitting on an
empty patch of land in rural
Virginia?

26:33.292 --> 26:37.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today is February 20, one month
into the new
Trump administration.

26:37.863 --> 26:41.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's an early moment to pause
and ask where
things stand.

26:41.200 --> 26:46.438 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
For that, we turn to our
Politics Monday team,
Tamara Keith of NPR and Amy
Walter of The

26:46.472 --> 26:48.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Cook Political Report.

26:48.407 --> 26:49.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And welcome to both of you.

26:49.508 --> 26:51.410 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It is Monday.

26:51.443 --> 26:55.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are already a month, as we
just said, Amy
and Tam, into this
administration.

26:55.981 --> 26:58.016 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, let's take a little bit of
stock.

26:58.050 --> 27:04.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tam, you have been looking at
the president's
appointments for big, important
positions,

27:04.089 --> 27:06.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the positions that have to be
confirmed by
the Senate.

27:06.592 --> 27:07.826 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What are you seeing?

27:07.860 --> 27:10.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How is he doing compared to
other presidents
at this point?

27:10.329 --> 27:13.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH, National Public
Radio: In terms
of getting them confirmed, he is
behind schedule.

27:13.465 --> 27:16.001 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's not entirely his fault.

27:16.034 --> 27:20.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Senate Democrats have been
slow-walking the
nominations, in part because
they say that

27:20.606 --> 27:24.376 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
many of these nominees are sort
of out of
line with the mainstream.

27:24.409 --> 27:28.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mitch McConnell, the Senate
Republican leader,
just the other day said that
this is the most

27:28.947 --> 27:31.049 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
conservative Cabinet he's seen.

27:31.083 --> 27:33.018 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Democrats take that as
validation of their
arguments.

27:33.051 --> 27:40.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But in terms of broadly, beyond
just the Cabinet,
the Senate-confirmed positions,
President

27:40.125 --> 27:43.161 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Trump has named 34 people so
far.

27:43.195 --> 27:48.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That is just slightly behind
pace of President
Obama and ahead of the pace of
President Bill

27:48.934 --> 27:51.236 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Clinton and President George W.
Bush.

27:51.270 --> 27:56.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So he's not actually behind,
despite many
stories saying, oh, my gosh,
he's behind.

27:56.842 --> 27:58.610 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Because you look
at some of
the numbers.

27:58.644 --> 28:05.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You said 500 -- you were telling
us 515 awaiting
confirmation, the 34 they have
named, and

28:05.350 --> 28:07.119 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
20 of them are still waiting.

28:07.152 --> 28:08.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
TAMARA KEITH: Right.

28:08.453 --> 28:11.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Amy, there is
a lot of
focus on these numbers.

28:11.290 --> 28:13.091 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How much does it matter?

28:13.125 --> 28:15.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMY WALTER, The Cook Political
Report: I think
there is the story about the
process and then

28:15.694 --> 28:17.296 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there's the story about the
perception.

28:17.329 --> 28:21.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that, as we learned
from Tam,
the process, he's not that far
off.

28:21.667 --> 28:27.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you look, again, academic
studies, President
Obama, by his first 100 days,
only had about

28:27.539 --> 28:29.074 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
17 percent of his appointees in.

28:29.107 --> 28:31.243 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, it's not the pace that's the
problem.

28:31.276 --> 28:33.478 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the perception that there's
chaos here.

28:33.512 --> 28:38.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some of it is about the people
that he's chosen
who have visions or views that
are different

28:38.884 --> 28:40.719 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
from the president's.

28:40.752 --> 28:44.056 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Ideologically, we don't really
still know
where the president is on a
whole lot of issues,

28:44.089 --> 28:45.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
where his North Star is.

28:45.924 --> 28:50.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, as you pointed out,
today, you had
the secretary of defense go to
Iraq and say,

28:50.262 --> 28:53.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know that the president
himself has said
we're going to come take your
oil.

28:53.665 --> 28:55.701 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Don't worry.

28:55.734 --> 28:57.469 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's one reason for that.

28:57.502 --> 29:01.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The other is a lot of talk about
this loyalty
test, so-called loyalty test for
people who

29:01.206 --> 29:02.975 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
want to be in high-level
positions.

29:03.008 --> 29:04.876 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Every president wants somebody
that is loyal
to them.

29:04.910 --> 29:07.512 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There is nothing wrong or
different about
that.

29:07.546 --> 29:11.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What is different, though, is
that it seems
to be taken to a level like we
haven't seen

29:11.450 --> 29:13.218 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
before.

29:13.251 --> 29:16.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you have written or said
anything during
the course of the campaign that
was critical

29:16.321 --> 29:22.094 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Donald Trump, you are not
going to be appointed
or you may lose a job that you
have been appointed

29:22.127 --> 29:25.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for once they find out what you
have actually
said.

29:25.197 --> 29:32.771 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So I think that's what lends
this idea that
this is sort of a Cabinet or a
process in

29:32.804 --> 29:34.606 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
chaos.

29:34.640 --> 29:37.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: And there were so
many people
in the so-called establishment,
so the people

29:37.042 --> 29:41.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that would be in line for these
sorts of positions,
that spoke out against Trump
during the campaign.

29:41.346 --> 29:42.481 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

29:42.514 --> 29:44.316 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There's a lot of material out
there to work
with.

29:44.349 --> 29:47.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, Tam, he said at his news
conference last
week: I have gotten more
accomplished in the

29:47.819 --> 29:51.857 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
first four weeks of my time in
office than,
he said, some presidents have
done in their

29:51.890 --> 29:53.759 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
entire term.

29:53.792 --> 29:57.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think a lot of people thought
that was hyperbole
and let him get away with a
little of that.

